04946nam a22006135i 9780226787152DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20212021ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226787152  a(DE-B1597)589329  a(OCoLC)1252426191  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aBV4647.F7bM657 2021 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a261.1090412231 aMoore, Brenna, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aKindred Spirits :bFriendship and Resistance at the Edges of Modern Catholicism /cBrenna Moore. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b12 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aClass 200: New Studies in Religion00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Spiritual Friendship as an Alternative Catholic Modernity -- t1. Between Latin America and Europe: Gabriela Mistral and the Maritains -- t2. “Luminous Spiritual Traces” to Islam: The Passionate Friendships of Louis Massignon -- t3. Marie- Magdeleine Davy and the Hermeneutic of Friendship in Resistance to Nazism -- t4. The Intimacy and Resilience of Invisible Friendship: Marie- Magdeleine Davy and Simone Weil -- t5. Friendship and the Black Catholic Internationalism of Claude McKay -- tEpilogue: Kindred Spirits as Fragments of Modernity -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aKindred Spirits takes us inside a remarkable network of Catholic historians, theologians, poets, and activists who pushed against both the far-right surge in interwar Europe and the secularizing tendencies of the leftist movements active in the early to mid-twentieth century. With meticulous attention to the complexity of real lives, Brenna Moore explores how this group sought a middle way anchored in “spiritual friendship”—religiously meaningful friendship understood as uniquely capable of facing social and political challenges. For this group, spiritual friendship was inseparable from resistance to European xenophobia and nationalism, anti-racist activism in the United States, and solidarity with Muslims during the Algerian War. Friendship, they believed, was a key to both divine and human realms, a means of accessing the transcendent while also engaging with our social and political existence. Some of the figures are still well known—philosopher Jacques Maritain, Nobel Prize laureate Gabriela Mistral, influential Islamicist Louis Massignon, poet of the Harlem renaissance Claude McKay—while others have unjustly faded from memory. Much more than an idealized portrait of a remarkable group of Catholic intellectuals from the past, Kindred Spirits is a compelling exploration of both the beauty and flaws of a vibrant social network worth remembering.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCatholic intellectuals. 0aCatholicsxIntellectual lifey20th century. 0aFriendshipxReligious aspectsxCatholic Church. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  afriendship, Catholicism, mysticism, fascism, modernity, transcendence, spirituality, resistance, friendship, France.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2021 Englishz978311075419308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2021z9783110753974oZDB-23-DGF08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073919040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226787152423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/docum